arch:note.arch:string: The purpose of the daily journal was to record the activities taking place in a trench each day. This included which loci were excavated, how and why loci were excavated and the ongoing impressions of the relationships among loci. It should be noted that journals record the actions, impressions and ideas of trench supervisors during the excavations. They are not, therefore, the final interpretations or syntheses of the emerging data.

arch:internalDocument.arch:string:
Daily Trench Journal

Area F, Trench 7

June 20, 2005

C. Painter

Today excavation continued in fill L7207 west of wall 7209. What appears to be a small wall stub is now visible in the southwest corner of the locus, however it seems to be "floating" in that it does not abut any features. Also uncovered in this southwest corner is a clustering of cobbles due north of wall 7201. These cobbles are only loosely associated and none seem to be grinding stone fragments or wall foundations. They are however located in interesting soil which varies in color from the pinkish gray (7.5 YR 7/2) soil color of fill 7207. A faint linear line north of the cobbles may suggest a wall line though in general the brick slump in this area of 7207 is very difficult to ascertain. Vigorous scrapping with trowels and cleaning in this area tomorrow will perhaps bring clearer features to light.

Work also progressed with plastered surface 7219, which was opened yesterday. Delicate excavation moving north, east and southward revealed that the floor does not extended further south than what was discovered yesterday, however the surface does continue north toward wall 7212 though whether or not the surface is actually bonded with this surface will need to be determined tomorrow. The floor also continues in a northeastern direction where it slopes up gently to meet an in situ door socket that is located in the northeast corner of the locus.

This door socket, however was found not to be related to any walls or other features and the surface at this point stops abruptly. It is possible on this eastern-most edge that a wall was excavated through and not noticed (this is certainly possible with a less substantial pisÃ© wall for example). Another possibility is that the surface does continue on this eastern side and we have yet to reach it, as it looks like we have not yet excavated low enough on this eastern side. Lastly I attempted to trace the floor into the northeast corner of L7211, seeing if perhaps it would connected with similar mud plaster surface 7213, which is north of wall 7210. These two surfaces did not connect however as there is a clear break.

Lastly a new pit locus (7221) was opened which cuts the center of platform 7183 in the southeast corner of the trench. It was noticed today that this "platform" was not paved across the top with mud bricks (i.e. it is not solid), but instead has a central pit which is lined with two yellow mud bricks on the edges (north and south) and two burnt mud bricks along the western edge. Thus far excavation in L7211, along with information from trench F2, has shown that L7183 is in fact composed of at least three courses of yellow bricks with a grayish/white mortar in between. Pit 7221 is a fine to medium silt matrix pit with poorly sorted, angular to rounded soil that was gray (7.5 YR 6/1) in color on the upper most level and underneath found to be a brown (7.5 YR 4/3) moist fine silt clay. This discrepancy in coloration I account to the length at which L7183 has been open and that the soil on the topmost levels has subsequently been dried out by both sun and wind.

7221 was excavated approximately 20 cm with hand trowel and was stopped when excavation became difficult since this is a rather enclosed space between the mud bricks of 7183 and the eastern baulk. Thus far very little in the way of finds were found, though a screening ratio of 1:1 was used through a ¼ inch sieve. A single carbon sample was taken, but overall this pit seems to contain sparse to no amounts of ash, some bone fragments and little pottery. Some small pebbles were recovered, some possibly being fire cracked. A soil sample was also collected at a middle depth within the pit.
